        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation experiment uses same geometry, fluid, and operating range as COU",
        "description": "The validation experiment must employ the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, bovine blood surrogate fluid, and the same five flow-speed operating points as the COU to ensure direct applicability of validation evidence."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry using bovine blood at physiologically representative conditions. All five COU operating points (flow rate 2–6 L/min, speed 2000–3500 RPM) were covered in the experimental campaign. The close correspondence between validation conditions and COU conditions satisfies Gradation 2 relevance requirements."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-nse-08",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error (iterative convergence error) is scoped out at MRL 2 because all simulations were run to residual convergence of 1×10⁻⁶ on all equations and monitored QoI values showed changes of less than 0.1% over the final 500 iterations, demonstrating negligible iterative error. Separate quantification beyond this monitoring is not required at Gradation 1/MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-ue-09",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU. The simulation workflow is executed by a single trained analyst team using a documented simulation protocol (SP-CBP-2024-001) with mandatory peer review of boundary condition setup and mesh quality metrics prior to production runs. The structured protocol and peer review control use-error risk to an acceptable level without formal independent re-execution."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-mf-10",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty (turbulence model selection, hemolysis power-law exponent) is scoped out at MRL 2. The SST k-ω turbulence model is the de facto standard for rotating blood pump CFD supported by multiple published validation studies. The Giersiepen–Wurzinger hemolysis power-law is the regulatory-accepted model for this device class. A sensitivity sweep over turbulence model variants (k-ε, RSM) was conducted informally and showed less than 4% variation in RH; formal model-form uncertainty quantification is not required at this risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-mi-11",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model input uncertainty (blood viscosity, density, pump geometric tolerances) is scoped out at MRL 2 because a Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis was performed as a supporting activity (not a required credibility factor at this risk level) and demonstrated that ±5% variation in viscosity and ±0.05 mm geometric tolerance produce less than 3% change in the RH QoI, confirming that input uncertainty does not materially affect the decision outcome."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cou1-ts-12",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Test samples factor is not applicable to this COU. The validation evidence is derived from in-vitro flow-loop experiments using a single FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry; there is no sample-to-sample manufacturing variability in the validation hardware because the pump geometry is a defined reference artifact, not a production sample population. Sample variability is therefore not a relevant credibility consideration for this assessment."
    },
